    "final_deliverable": "## Topic A \u2014 Tardigrades in astrobiology (from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade)\n\n### (1) Extreme conditions tardigrades survive (at least two)\nWikipedia explicitly lists multiple severe conditions individual tardigrade species can survive: \n- **Extreme temperatures**: The page says tardigrades can survive \u201c**exposure to extreme temperatures**\u201d (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026with individual species able to survive severe conditions, such as exposure to **extreme temperatures**, extreme pressures (both high and low), air deprivation, radiation, dehydration, and starvation\u2026*\u201d\n- **Extreme pressures (high and low)**: Same sentence includes \u201c**extreme pressures (both high and low)**\u201d (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026exposure to extreme temperatures, **extreme pressures (both high and low)**, air deprivation\u2026*\u201d\n- **Air deprivation / lack of oxygen**: The article lists both \u201c**air deprivation**\u201d (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026air deprivation\u2026*\u201d and later \u201c**lack of oxygen**\u201d (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026they become highly resistant to environmental stresses, including\u2026 **lack of oxygen**, vacuum, ionising radiation, and high pressure.*\u201d\n- **Radiation**: It lists \u201c**radiation**\u201d among survivable conditions (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026air deprivation, **radiation**, dehydration, and starvation\u2026*\u201d\n- **Dehydration**: It lists \u201c**dehydration**\u201d as survivable (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026radiation, **dehydration**, and starvation\u2026*\u201d\n- **Vacuum**: In the \u201ctun\u201d state they resist \u201c**vacuum**\u201d (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*\u2026highly resistant to environmental stresses, including\u2026 **vacuum**, ionising radiation\u2026*\u201d\n\n(Any two of the above satisfy the requirement; I\u2019ve provided more with direct quotes.)\n\n### (2) One named space-exposure experiment\nA named space-exposure experiment is the **FOTON-M3 mission (2007)**. Wikipedia states (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade): \u201c*In 2007, dehydrated tardigrades were taken on the **FOTON-M3 mission** and exposed to vacuum, or to both vacuum and solar ultraviolet, for 10 days.*\u201d\n\nIt also notes additional space context (not required, but evidentiary): \u201c*Tardigrades have survived exposure to space.*\u201d (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tardigrade)\n\n---\n\n## Topic B \u2014 Brutalist architecture (missing primary evidence from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brutalist_architecture)\n\nThe task requires visiting https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brutalist_architecture and extracting (1) at least two defining characteristics and (2) one example building **with exact URL citations and verbatim quotes**.\n\nHowever, in the provided materials, **RAW VISIT CONTENT for https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brutalist_architecture is not included**\u2014only partial \u201cRetrieved Memories\u201d metadata (mostly link lists) appears, and it does **not contain the article\u2019s textual statements** needed to quote characteristics or name a building from the page.\n\nBecause the mandate requires that every fact be supported by a quote from the visited page text, I cannot truthfully provide Brutalist characteristics or an example building from that Wikipedia page using the supplied evidence.\n\nWhat is present (but insufficient): the memory confirms the page was visited (\u201cVisit https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brutalist_architecture, action=visit, success=True\u201d), but provides no definitional sentences or building examples to quote.\n\n---\n\n## Comparative paragraph (cannot be completed as specified)\n\nA 100+ word comparative paragraph drawing a thematic parallel between **tardigrade resilience** and **Brutalist